    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The history of unions in the US dates back to the late 19th century, with the formation of the Knights of Labor in 1869, which advocated for an 8-hour workday and better working conditions. The Industrial Workers of the World (IWW) emerged in 1905, pushing for a unified union that covered all industries. The formation of the AFL (American Federation of Labor) in 1886, led by Samuel Gompers, marked a shift towards more modest union goals and the development of craft-specific unions. In the mid-20th century, the CIO (Congress of Industrial Organizations) merged with the AFL and continued the fight for better wages and working conditions. Lately, unions have faced challenges, including decreased collective bargaining power and rising income inequality, but a resurgence of interest in unionization has occurred in recent years.",
